
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `infocmp` baraye moghayese va namayeshe etela'ate terminalha estefade mishavad. Yani etela'ate "capability" haye terminalharo ba ham moghayese mikone ya etela'ate yek terminal ro namayesh mide.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `infocmp` --> 📜 Namayesh etela'ate terminale pishfarz.
    🔹 `infocmp -x` --> ➕ Namayesh hameye etela'at, hata extension-ha.
    🔹 `infocmp -d term1 term2` --> 📏 Moghayese `term1` va `term2` va namayeshe tafavotha.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ infocmp

    🔹 Namayesh etela'ate terminale pishfarz (ke az $TERM gerefte shode).

    $ infocmp -d xterm-256color screen-256color

    🔹 Moghayese terminalhaye `xterm-256color` va `screen-256color` va namayeshe tafavotha.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ infocmp -x

    🔹 Namayeshe hameye capability ha va extension ha baraye terminale pishfarz.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `infocmp` command is used to compare and display terminal information. It compares the "capabilities" of terminals or displays information about a specific terminal.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `infocmp` --> 📜 Display information for the default terminal.
    🔹 `infocmp -x` --> ➕ Display all information, including extensions.
    🔹 `infocmp -d term1 term2` --> 📏 Compare `term1` and `term2` and show the differences.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ infocmp

    🔹 Display information for the default terminal (taken from $TERM).

    $ infocmp -d xterm-256color screen-256color

    🔹 Compare the `xterm-256color` and `screen-256color` terminals and display the differences.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ infocmp -x

    🔹 Display all capabilities and extensions for the default terminal.

